The Prague stock exchange was down to negative at the end of the trading
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague stock exchange recovered its losses.
The transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the trade, the Prague stock exchange was rebounded with its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the drop is due to the fall in Wall Street stock.
The market reaction to the result of the vote in the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilisation plan, is thus also felt in our country.
The fall in stocks in Asia
The Asian stock market fell dramatically on Tuesday, although the indices managed to erase some losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange's Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the drop to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange fell 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
Sydney Stock Exchange was down more than five percent, but it was finally able to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation about the U.S. bailout will affect financial markets around the world", observed Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should resume negotiations soon and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries could be affected.
The bloodshed of American stocks
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the financial system support bill, which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion Kč).
The legislators thus rejected the call for support for President George Bush's bill.
According to Bush, the project should address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the economy as a whole.
US stocks were in a bloodbath on Monday and the main stock indexes were in the worst decline in 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, having seen a fall of this magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gave in: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to a vote early next week.
The US legislature made a decisive turn in the negotiations on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the US financial system.
Success is not certain, though.
Indeed, before the final version of the bill can be published and put to a vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial support plan will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
This was reported to Reuters on Sunday by Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee.
According to sources, the plan should be put to a vote in the Senate by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement of the rescue plan should be the first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market support can be effective, a 'disillusionment' will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form the package of measures for market stabilization should take", said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, to Bloomberg.
She said the final vote could be held on Sunday.
On Saturday night, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government a final form.
The latter should buy back from financial companies non-marketable real estate assets that cause financial firms to suffer significant losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we are there", says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling stock markets.
Democratic Senator Harry Reid said lawmakers are getting Congress to reach a final agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading begins on the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect Monday's trading.
But at the moment it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will vote, or whether negotiations may be blocked at the last moment by a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be passed in the coming days.
However, the law will still be subject to many changes.
The total amount allocated to the scheme must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not doing its job, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount by following two steps: First an additional $100 billion, and then finally, $350 billion.
Mr Bush welcomed the progress made in the negotiations
While the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of making it a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to raise funds to buy back bad real estate securities, whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday", said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of gold parachutes
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Chief Negotiator Christopher Dodd, says lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, taxpayer protection from losses, the settlement of deductions, the timeline of the plan.
The new law also provides for the limitation of the gold parachutes for directors of the companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans", said Paulson.
The plan also provides for assistance for property owners who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new settlements for mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And this is because we don't know what the mechanism and the price of the asset buyback will be.
This will be a decisive point in deciding on the loss sharing between the financial sector and the government", Marek told iHNed.cz.
Whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is not as important, according to Marek.
"It is much more important that the Members of Parliament agree, as of this week, to support this plan and to dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, which provides for the adoption of the plan, is most important at this time", Marek stressed.
