The first virtual operator will be in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I can .
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering almost the same services as their Western European partners.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for long.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz many times that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which reported that the price of SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation: SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple: there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration rate that is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators often complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that there is no longer room for another operator in the Czech Republic, is choosing to join the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network seems to be less fortunate (in fact, it would be difficult to find frequencies at present).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable price decline, which was subsequently also to be met by traditional operators.
Yet even before the turmoil of such parties as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile came to market, voices similar to those we hear in our homes today were heard in Britain.
But it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could be truly successful.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the mobile operator Mobilking.
In just six months, the operator has managed to gain over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
The Bank's main business is the Bank of Greece, which is responsible for the financing of the Bank of Greece.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they require far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
In this way, virtual operators around the world are portrayed as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and text messages, which is often offset by a limited range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would work in our own country.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesman, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segment approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services".
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
It seems almost certain, however, that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area", Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try their best to keep a potential competitor from appearing.
GTS Novera, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of enterprise customers, has not hidden for quite some time its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some we have succeeded in making progress in the negotiations", says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be bright.
From unofficial information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by a complete silence.
'At the moment we do not believe there is any place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
At the moment, we have not been contacted by any complex and serious project in this area", said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally beneficial project that could serve as a basis".
She added: "It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate within such a limited time frame, we should have a concrete agreement now".
Vodafone is focusing on fulfilling the requests for its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think means the most from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.'
The responsible authorities: in line with the operators
The move by mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
What good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
The Commission's proposal for a directive on the protection of workers' rights and the right to a fair trial is a major step forward.
The biggest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ when the U:fon was created was by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ's webpages.
Today, however, the U:fon is being used as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented on this: 'Competition on the mobile market has also recently been enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the RT mobile market, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and above all its services, to high demands.'
But given the attitude of mobile operators, the indifference of Czech regulators seems puzzling.
This is not the only attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike Britain and other developed countries, does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
The Office is the sole owner of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OPC).
The latter took his typical position on this issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, as the offer from potential stakeholders has not a priori shown sufficient interest for the traditional operators,' explained Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS Foreign Affairs Department in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not come as a surprise from operators' representatives.
But from an office which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual operators are normally present, their entry into the market has contributed to a decline in the prices of mobile telephone services".
However, pressure to ensure the fair functioning of the market and the reduction of prices is apparently not in the interests of the HSEO.
What is shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
Similarly, a price for gasoline which is strictly the same for all petrol stations is likely due to chance and to the fierce competition.
'The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for its market behaviour.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even for the telecoms regulator,' Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets drawn up by the ČTÚ that telecommunications constitute a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at all times.
And the mobile operator logically has a monopoly on its network.
It thus necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least concerning to the OHIM that three mobile operators are clearly acting in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera mentioned above) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
The return of responsibility to the ČTÚ is a fairly common communication tactic whereby the ÚOHS washes its hands of the matter.
We have encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Law failed to introduce an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised an improvement in the situation.
This is something that the representatives of the OHIM must be aware of, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can walk.
However, the operation of some kind of virtual pseudo-operators, many of them in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a multi-level marketing company.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer personalized mobile phone services.
The price lists of these firms are usually only available to elected officials.
The magic trick is that the company is in front of the operator as a typical business customer, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special offers for prices (and other)
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are saying happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions we are looking at and could lead to a cessation of cooperation with the company in question", Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the mobile operators' officials.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers may be involved.
No operator, however, opposes such a procedure.
The fact is that these firms' activities bring them considerable profits, and at the same time, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name and therefore cannot be fully available to them, as ordinary mobile operator customers do.'
This is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises at the UOHS.
If mobile operators are not aware of such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has relatively wide powers to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim that they have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we're not the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant drop in the price of services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators sometimes tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were almost the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
This is precisely what the regulatory bodies in developed countries did, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they eventually achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities treat this issue like a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it to a nearby target.
In the light of our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that confusion in skills is more than beneficial in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the hammer.
If the background information is true and a virtual operator appears in our home soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it is difficult for the ÚOHS to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four recordings of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech National Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my country?).
The national anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, a choral performance and an instrumental version.
The song is sung by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the hymn.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers and the choir had a good diction, so that the lyrics could be understood well, and they could sing at the same time", he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th birthday next year.
Kde domov můj was first sung in 1834 on the stages of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Scholars' Kermesse), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
