Prague public transport (PHD) will introduce chip in its ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be entered in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pockets.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about 100,000 people, who own the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and register it on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, coupons can also be purchased online on the Dopravní podnik website: www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people benefited from the service during the morning.
Those who start using the online store may forget the ticket counters at the subway stations, where they have hitherto had to walk impatiently in long queues in order to get paper tickets.
They will purchase their voucher online and will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"At these contact points, passengers have a shop with trained staff, who will assist them with online purchases and also record the coupon they purchased on their card", says Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to register electronic vouchers on Opencard in vending machines installed in the halls of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, recall the ticket composting machines, and passengers may have noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská subway stations.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year, it should be eighty", Opatrný added.
A vending machine will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automata that will be running from tomorrow, they're easy to use.
You just need to enter the Opencard smart card and the coupon you bought earlier will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the city's surroundings.
The main routes are the suburban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia to reach the capital.
"On trains integrated in Pražská integrovaná doprava (integrated transport in Prague), controllers are equipped with card readers, which they use to establish the temporary and zonal validity of coupons", explained ticket controller Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation, which designs the schedules of Prague's public transport.
Suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver's register.
When boarding, the driver must not only see the smart card, but also place the Opencard at the point indicated on the side of the box.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing easier than to ask the driver for this information", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take the suburban buses and do not remember the expiry date of their coupon may rejoin the vending machines, which were originally used to store the coupons on the card.
This is where the document validity information will be displayed on the device's screen.
