In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans were supposedly addressing the president of the United States with such a desire.
This is the result of a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
The Germans in Český Krumlov wrote to the US President asking that the "šumavská župa" (forest region in southern Bohemia) annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement should not be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation well and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", says the letter, signed "Persons who care about the fate of the Šumava".
Since the alleged promise of joining Czechoslovakia - in the Czech national character - is only brutality, disregard, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the US President to take over the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would give this territory to a State alien to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has done nothing to help the Allies win without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million people", the letter said.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is fear of the desire for vengeance of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubted the views of the Germans in Šumava, he would have to hold a referendum in the region to decide whether the people wanted to be part of the US or live under US patronage.
Although the text of the letter may seem a little naive, some survivors say, given the current knowledge of postwar history, it well illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of that time.
While the Czech Germans had at least anticipated the question of their expulsion from the republic, very few of them admitted that possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to gain some sort of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others thought they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
During the war, he was, as a German from České Budějovice, enlisted in the Baltic Navy.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in the Holstein concentration camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They thought that when they returned home, the Czech would be beneficial", says Chalupa.
He said that none of the captured Germans living in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that Beneš's decrees would expel them from the republic.
