Rats have sensations too
A rat or cockroach running away from danger, does that mean he feels fear too?
Neurophysician Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we know that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
The online magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions for several years by renowned scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that neither I nor anyone else has been able to prove until now, just as we cannot prove that other humans have a conscience.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter into areas that are difficult to practice because the hardware doesn't fit.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, runs away or attacks.
Humans behave in a similar way, which is why some scientists conclude that a similar subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transpose our subjective experiences into those of animals.
One aspect is that circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in directional and executive functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other beings.
So at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including our consciousness of who we are, and our ability to foresee and decide, it's reasonable to assume that humans are even different from other primates.
Another significant feature may lie in the linguistic nature of man: as much of his existence is linked to language, it often means that his conscience depends on it.
In that case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if the conscience were not to depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what the conscience of other animals may look like.
If this, internal and subjective, cannot be measured or analyzed by this particular hardware based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
You could look at the processes of animal consciousness without considering their content, and that's exactly what happened in studies of primate short-term memory, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which was followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the neural correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Strangely, this approach also highlights the prefrontal cortex's weight in making visualization.
But what about the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the state of mind in which we find ourselves when the activity of the local defense system in the brain (or its effects, like body reactions) takes over the living memory.
Emotions are closely related to the areas of the cortex that characterize primates, and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volatile nature, are evident, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impose them on others than ourselves.
On the contrary, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the body sensation regions of the cortex and brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could quite participate in cross-sectional sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict this, but I believe it is indisputable.
Pankseep argues that what is fear in both men and rats is likely to be felt as well in both cases: how could one verify if rats and men feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if he feels fear?
I don't think that the same behavior is enough to prove the same experiences.
True, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain stem, but cockroaches don't even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the source of sensations?
And even if we could prove this to man, how could we prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior over the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is striking on the nervous level as the same measurement is made in rats and humans.
Since I don't explore the language and consciousness in rats, or sensations, I don't know if they exist.
You could think of it as a short-term deal, but I'd rather move forward than keep hitting a wall.
I'm actually a pragmatic emotionalist.
