Hidden in the development of its vast park, a few miles from the sunny, bright, giant Orlando, lies a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, the first all-black town to be incorporated, home of Zora Neale Hurston's childhood, that description she made in 1935, is no longer so simple to make nowadays". The city with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of goyaves, two schools and no prison".
It has now become a pilgrimage city
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora Festival in Eatonville to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in various ways, the city she describes - which has become a tourist destination thanks to its inclusion in the Florida tourist guide published by The Depression-era Federal Writers' Project - remains a distinct place.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston reported that the black rural population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who"knows so little about us, doesn't know what he's missing".
Even though this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has also called for open dialogue on the theme of race, many here remain cautious of foreign eyes.
