"it must be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It represents both a historic model of a black takeover of power and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of the rural black culture of the South - sometimes despised, sometimes acclaimed - that recalls the birth of slavery in America.
Which would explain why the residents are both proud and protective.
Interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through sincere, dialect-filled books, such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide turned this city, located just off the exit of Highway 17, into a road that runs through central Florida, often forgotten, that ends in a chapter of black history and human drama.
As bold as a big box in life as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was then divided into several private parts.
"On the left side of the road", she writes, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its gardens and these well-preserved playgrounds that Howard Miller has always taken care of, although he can barely read or write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn" sells all kinds of drinks as well as anything that can be of use to passersby.
