"People were always happy to see Zora", he said.
But he adds, swinging in his backyard chair overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was certainly baptized, that "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in some grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she lived.
In Eatonville, no big memorial, no plaque for the general public.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy it brought to the world", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
