"I photograph the master off stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes from strangers.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to achieve the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
The other person.
They're inseparable except in the privacy of those moments unknown to the general public, where you discover, through intimate gestures and stolen looks, artists who don't care to get on stage.
German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco - people" blends the theatrical aspects of a few stages with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, which grows every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists who can convey passion, sadness, joy on stage... captivating the audience.
To capture the personality moments of these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a character.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with my camera the personality moments of flamenco stars".
With the "Popular Song of the Mines" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a record camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, reminds me of classic photography.
The use of different styles breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, reflecting Bauer's perception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the dance or the singing itself, but the personality and character of the artist who captures the audience with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work which is being presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are among the selected artists from around seventy photographed artists.
The project has become a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a collection of portraits on display at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts differ in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph people, get to know them and be able to enter their lives for a moment or less.
I think in photography, portraiture is the hardest kind.
You're facing people, characters you don't know, or people who just give you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I still try to make my ideas come true".
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 of the Mata Street (a street parallel to the Peupleraie in Hercules) which will be open until 16 October.
