Talking while sleeping
Some kids talk at night.
I'm not talking about those who wake up very much by telling us about something that happened the day before, but about the children who talk while they're sleeping.
The first time it happens, it might surprise you, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a mild sleep disturbance called somniloquy.
It's quite common, especially in children and teenagers.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, in association with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child has lost all memory.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often associated with other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night dizziness (bed peeing) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As mentioned earlier, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations, or over-excitement.
It's a little-studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity of the reaction is also highly variable.
He may speak in a quiet, small voice, with private words, with murmurs, or, on the contrary, with screams, tears, long speeches...
If sleepwalking becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We said it's a mild disorder, so there's no treatment unless it's related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it's related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to arouse the child before going to bed.
Therefore, seek out calm games and avoid television programs or series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
As soon as sleepwalking appears, try to stay calm.
Remember, they are harmless to the child and the next day he will not remember what happened.
Helpful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember, if the child is experiencing severe anxiety several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or to find out what is causing such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not usual), do not be tempted to ask questions for information.
You're not going to get anything, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thinking.
You may also hear what he is saying, but you may not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell a child that you can question him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even in a joke.
It causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's not a bad thing, it's just a few minutes long.
