Interview - Blood is safe again
HEMA-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as HEMA-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the public's trust that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public outcry, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, in February 1994, to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was delaying his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and the two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, only 38 percent of people in Quebec still trusted the blood system", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and field work in the years since, we have regained public confidence", she says, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population now trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, remembers that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
From its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, Europe was witnessing the outbreak of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the disease that has been the dominant form since its inception in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when this is not known and a serious disease may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, blood was refused to those who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago it was clearly shown that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This incident showed us that the precautionary principle was a good one".
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique was introduced: nucleic acid tests (NTAs), which allow the presence of the virus itself to be directly detected in the blood of donors and not antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used up to that time were based.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which runs from the time the person is infected to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, says the expert.
We were able to reduce this to less than a week.
This has significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected unwittingly and untraceable.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of contracting HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it will take 12 million blood products to be distributed before anyone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products annually, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that one can feel comfortable today receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health", says the head of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not long after last year, Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Decary, before stressing that in addition to secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"The need is increasing because the population is aging.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to be refilled with red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population is also affecting the blood donors' network, which on average comprises only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation".
However, anyone who is 18 years of age or older and who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but more importantly, to keep them from giving and to encourage them to become regular donors.
"We are so busy in today's world that we rarely have time to spend an hour donating blood", says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and are planning to take more than a thousand a year.
The idea is that transplants should be available early next year", says Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
