Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its 17 September issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following Orwellian logic, the paper claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a $6 million defamation suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house in an attempt to launch a "transparent public debate".
While judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in defamation cases, but the law.
It is not surprising that this fundamental difference is completely overlooked by Mr Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will scare the opposition and frighten anyone who dares to look at the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually held by exchange of ideas, not by batting.
The mining industry was therefore able to open up its books and files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the matter.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and has rejected petitions and letters of support for the Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can both call for a 'public' debate while disregarding the views of that same public?
In the vice president's world, it seems that this word only refers to the high-paid lawyers and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have a say.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the writers and editors of Black Canada is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but not on the basis of civilized exchange of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a "bully pursuit" (in pursuit of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a notice against the authors of Black Canada urging them to stop using the term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold prosecution is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in its entirety, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are not pleasing to the rich corporations of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of repeated prosecutions, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the writers of Black Canada.
She has a right to retaliate.
The academic community to which we belong has long been a master at handling debates and disagreements and resolving conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution makes it clear that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the academic world, as it is to the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
