"Everything has been done to shield the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"This is the bottom line: If we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to American daily life will be immense", said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had been on the brink in the last few hours for fear of the effect of a further failure on the investors' mood.
The deadline we agreed was the markets opening this morning.
The two candidates for the US presidential election, who were late in the negotiations, were rather favourable to the agreement, but they were also dissatisfied with the fact that this had to be done.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has said that some provisions have been added to the agreement, including one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and one on the salaries of the heads of the state-owned businesses.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be flattered about.
