Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so".
"The broad lines I have read [shows] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and we're going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to use taxpayer money to buy back dubious, risky, unsold assets from U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (sub-loans) before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze in liquidity and the bankruptcy of banks and financial institutions.
It's a group of Republican voters who had the first draft of the bill overturned last week.
It is believed that this deadlock has been lifted since the Democrats accepted that some of the "toxic" assets of the struggling companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
To make matters easier for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to take five years' worth of losses with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for a first tranche of 250 billion, which can be added to an additional 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
