What could Zuschlag &amp; Company have been producing in their invoice factory?
The hearings on the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are charged with fraud, as a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, causing particularly serious damage.
The prosecutor's office said that the money from the grants was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The state and municipal funds, which totalled about HUF 65 million, went to the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and to the pockets of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to make money from the grants obtained by issuing invoices of fees, behind which no actual benefit was provided and thus the associations never fulfilled their commitments.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were fake.
They obtained invoice books for the latter at the market in Józsefváros, while they made the cigarettes in Kiskunhalas.
The names of the companies to be included in the invoices were decided, inter alia, during the tours of the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the witness's testimony, he was supposed to be spotting boarding houses and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he requested an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices they were to introduce, among others, with the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour and the Capital Municipality to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drawing up the documents necessary for obtaining the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, the place provided for the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy the place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice issued for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which later became known as Egütt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and a maximum of ten people could stay overnight, but the bill mentioned 130 customers.
The overwhelmingly imaginative invoicers also fell into excess when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, which also belongs to the Horeca sector.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were fake documents.
"Our company name and tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp".
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, 100 people were staying there, was also not a problem, since the establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
Besides, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time".
The enthusiastic invoice issuers also did not inquire about the travel agencies of Budapest, which were part of their choice but only organised travel abroad.
Moreover, as it appeared from the investigation, they also added VAT to these documents, while benefits for travel activities, which are destined outside the European Union, are charged VAT-free.
Similarly, the VAT rate on the four invoices issued on behalf of the Hotel Révfülöp by order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's benefits do not bear a 25% VAT as indicated, but a 15% VAT.
The investigation by the Prosecutor's Office reveals that the 'issuers' also made mistakes in referring to the transport of goods by road as a service, which the invoice issuing company could not exercise, given that its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it is also for irregularities in form, such as types of inadequate invoices and false seals, that the invoices issued by the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont were found to be false.
The same is true of Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó's sports training company, both of which deny that they are the authors of invoices issued in their name.
The counterfeiters also failed to pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was supposed to have a meal at their home.
Invoices prepared deliberately
Another category of invoice issuers is those who were fully aware that they were required to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the grouping of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has drawn up an invoice for the foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért for a sum of HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and in 2003 issued invoices for the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület Association, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but no benefits were actually provided.
There was also no financial movement, as the invoices issued were later cancelled, but the authorities avoided mentioning this in their accounts.
The next category of companies issuing invoices is those directly related to the defendants.
The administrative representative of the managing director of Delta Trió Kft., which was responsible for the fuel and automotive trade, was Ivan Kubatov, whose headquarters were in Budapest but where he was not present.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, these equipment were allegedly purchased by Kiskunhalas' Cash Investment Kft., which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Ivan Kubatov was also reported to have sent documents relating to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, during the investigation Kubatov admitted that he issued invoices for the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and de Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and that he pocketed their counter value.
It was at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian masons established the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies were operating, which the accused explained by the fact that they were not getting jobs.
He nevertheless used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused and the draftsman of the company's founding documents, he had invoices drawn up on their behalf, in the order of associations related to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov has given 15 invoices to organisations, in total, issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor thought that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices and VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices which were used in the course of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a grant application to the socialist party's public benefit organization, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They received this subsidy for a double amount of HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes stated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
In fact, these bills were found during the search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, a part of the defendants will report on the method of invoicing, as they had done before the prosecutor's office.
What might be really interesting would be that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest or whether, possibly, the Socialists would have made an agreement that in exchange for the repayment of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would wear the hat alone.
Today, the latter is probably upset, since requests for his residence under surveillance, based on a reduction in his conditions of detention, are constantly in the ears of deaf people.
The Commission has not yet decided whether to proceed with the procedure, but it has decided to proceed with the procedure.
Psychology of over-auction: why spend more money?
When auctioning, buyers tend to spend more and overestimate the goods.
Neurological and economic researchers at New York University have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be excluded from this type of competition, such as an eBay auction, and they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to establish a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" by using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, while the other group participated in a play auction, while the researchers used a functional magnetic resonance imaging (FRI) method to analyze the brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, where a key element was the over-auction of a third, the whole under the brainstem, called the striatum, became intensely mobile when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believe that the rise in prices is due to the leakage of the striatum's violent reaction.
In support of their theories, the economists in this group of researchers carried out financial monitoring analyses.
In these, three groups overbid one partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question and they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if they won the game, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
While the third group got the $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money if they lost the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that the focus was on one group's victory, while the other group's focus was on failure.
In this way, the team members of the "failure" players were willing to bet higher than the control group and the "win" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Each of these explanations was based on the pleasure of winning and the risk of risk.
Only neurological imaging has helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories, now leading to a third explanation". - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
There are an estimated 100 miles of hepatitis virus patients in Hungary, but only seven miles are being treated, because often the patients do not know they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms, with liver inflammation and jaundice being characteristic, but the pathogens and the diseases they cause are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g.: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers are advised to get vaccinated against A and B viruses anyway.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor overall health, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then on the skin and white of the eye, a visible yellowishness develops, stool becomes lighter and urine becomes darker in color.
Worldwide, one million people die each year from the most serious form of the disease, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they have the virus, because the pathogen subtly destroys liver cells, and in many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening is very important.
The contamination rate is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoo artists.
Currently, there are an estimated 200 million people worldwide with chronic hepatitis C.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured if detected in time, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
The aim is to draw attention to the chronic cirrhosis of the liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to recent research, religious belief would work as a sort of pain reliever, which would have already helped make Catholic martyrs more tolerable to die.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article that researchers at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment in analyzing the extent to which belief in God could influence human tolerance of pain.
In this strange experiment, 12 Catholics and as many atheists were electrocuted while each of them looked at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to rule out much of the suffering.
Using a human brain palpation technique, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment is conducted as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electric shocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look continuously at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not much different from the first, had a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time received 20 electric shocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed painting.
Catholics said that seeing the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", "cared for", and "calmed down and peace prevailed".
When they saw the religious-themed painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image that they react very positively to, say, a mother or father", said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, actually changes our personality", Wright added.
After these excellent results, the only question remains what effect would it have on the regulation of subjects' pain if the faithful were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or a painter of the same calibre?
Would seeing a better quality of the Virgin Mary produce better results?
