The Warsaw Stock Exchange makes a proposal to buy the Prague Stock Exchange
The Warsaw Stock Exchange offered €200 million, or about 5 billion Czech crowns, to buy 100% of the shares of the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, the chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed the proposal made by the Poles despite the Czech authorities having previously excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the circle of potential new owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason for this exclusion is that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is in the hands of the state.
99% of the shares are held by the Polish State, which wants to separate more than 60% of its shares within a few months of operations.
According to the Czech economic daily E15, the Polish proposal represents the highest bid ever made for the purchase of the Prague stock exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the Nasdaq Transatlantic Stock Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Börse have made an offer so far.
Petr Koblic, the director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among those interested, the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the new least-suited owner, and did not rule out the fact that this could lead to the demise of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague stock exchange is estimated by market experts to be between 5 and 10 billion Czech crowns.
Under a deal between the shareholders, some 90% of the papers would be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is investment bank Patria Finance, with around 25 per cent stake, followed by the 14.7 per cent stake in Ceská Sporitelna Bank and Tiger Holding Four S.a.r.l. with 13.5 per cent.
