The smart car mimics the steering wheel
What better method to develop technologies to avoid an obstacle than to imitate an obstacle detector already in existence in nature?
Like the one about bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the starting strategy to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C type self-driving robot control system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee forms its own oval-shaped space, which in fact looks very much like our secure protective shell - said Kazuhhiro Doi, the head of the brand's research and development and technology relations department.
The bee's faceted eye plays a vital role, as it is capable of seeing in all directions at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers have approached the idea of the laser telescope.
The system identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres from the BR23C, assesses the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns it into a maneuver of avoidance.
The detection of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second, and then the mini-auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning them at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the mini-robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility and Robotic Car Project Laboratory.
It must act instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collision is currently considered unavoidable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotational motion, acceleration and slowdown as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot.
BR23C uses lighter Lithium polymer batteries with a higher energy concentration, which makes their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
Andoh says instinctive intelligent response is paramount, not data processing, much less storage capacity.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It doesn't have to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilo-octets of memory continuously.
We don't need a memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even a megabyte.
This is the first step towards the design of an instantaneous avoidance technology, and Nissan estimates that the system will be rolled out to mass-produced cars within the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his way.
