Reuters reports that during new debates lasting until midnight on Saturday, local time on the east coast, congressional leaders agreed on the days-long controversy surrounding the total $700 billion bailout plan.
"We have taken a serious step forward", said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic chairwoman of the U.S. House of Representatives, adding that the only thing left to do is to write the agreements down.
The compromise, born of the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, commented on the compromise results and said that the programme would work and be effective, but that further measures still need to be implemented.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8pm local time in Washington (i.e. Monday at 2am local time in Central Europe), but did not cause a dramatic increase in the stock market.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill that is the equivalent of the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The programme also differs from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion should be spent in one go to buy back securities on doubtful loans.
From now on, half of the $700 billion can be spent, with the first $250 billion being issued immediately after the bill is passed by Congress, probably on Monday, and the first amount going to the Treasury Secretary to buy questionable bank debt, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The programme will be supervised by an independent body, in which the Chairman of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
