Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1% compared to July 2008, while they decreased by 3.9% compared to a year earlier.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7% compared to the previous month and by 3.2% compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only slightly: 0.1% compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors have only slightly increased by 0.1% compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was seen in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8%), with firstly bag and belt manufacturing with a monthly increase of 4.6%, followed by footwear production with a monthly increase of 2.5%.
The higher levels of prices for plastics and chemicals have led to a considerable monthly increase in prices for the manufacturing of products and chemicals sector (1.6%).
This resulted in a deflation in the oil processing sector (1.4%), in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9%), and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, printing and printing remained the same.
Other sectors of the processing industry increased by between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which play a major role in national industrial production, prices rose by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a comparison of 12 months, the most significant increase (32.4%) was seen in the prices of the oil processing sector, taking into account domestic sales of the processing industries.
In the metalworking sector, prices increased by 13.2%, while in the major food, beverage and tobacco industries, prices increased by 11%.
Prices fell in the textile and textile products sectors (2.5%) and in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3%).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 to 9.1 percent.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water sectors surpassed the previous year's by 18.7 per cent.
Among the groups of domestic trade and by sector, the sectors that generated the most significant monthly increase in prices (0.7%) in August were those that generated the most profit on investment.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3%, while those in the energy and processing sectors were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest increase was observed in the energy and materials production sectors for further processing (16.8%) compared to the same month of the previous year.
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was 6.8%, while in the profit-making sectors, inflation was 1.4%.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1,1% in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3,9% over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment rate against the euro has weakened by 1.7 percent, against the dollar by 7.1 percent, and against the euro by 7.5 percent and against the dollar by 15.9 percent, compared with August 2007.
