Járóka said: We must break the cycle of poverty and segregation
The European Summit on Equality of Opportunities, hosted by France, as representative of the current Presidency of the European Union, has opened today in Paris.
In her speech to the plenary as one of the main speakers of the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP from the European People's Party Fidesz, drew attention to segregation in education as a violation of the right that most affects Roma children and thus one of the main barriers to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, the French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and by Vladimir Spidla, the European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The persons invited to participate in the consultation include the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of European legal protection and civil society bodies in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the Fidesz Parti Popular group, Járóka warned that apart from the distinctions seen in hiring, Roma are disappearing from the labour market primarily because of their low qualifications.
"The overwhelming majority of Roma youths do not have a high school diploma, and as a result of poor primary education, only a small percentage have the opportunity to obtain a graduate degree".
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in upholding other fundamental rights.
Investing in early childhood education for Roma means strengthening the economies of the EU Member States.
The European Parliament has also called for a European Parliament to be formed to support the efforts of the European Parliament to achieve a European Union-wide dialogue on the subject.
The earlier a Rom child starts school, the more likely he is to become a productive member of the labour market; he contributes to the state budget by taxes paid on his income and consumption.
"As citizens of the European Union, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education and be protected from low quality and sectarian education", said Járóka.
The European Union's objective-oriented cooperation and action are needed to accelerate the process of de-segregation of schools immediately, and for this reason it is of paramount importance that the existing anti-discrimination directives be complied with and prepared.
"We must break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, and give Roma children the democratic opportunities they need to participate as full citizens in the future of Europe", Járóka demanded.
In the name of the European Year for Equality of Opportunities for All, the objective of the European Summit for Equality of Opportunities, which has been held annually since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination at European and Member State level.
