No opposition MP has entered the Belarusian parliament after Sunday's elections.
According to Russian observers, this is due to a country led by Alexander Lukashenko, which ensures prosperity and stability, while according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), this is due to illegal voting practices.
The OSCE, which has sent 450 observers from 43 countries, does not recognize the elections.
Although the 110-member legislature in the country of 10 million people has been under great opposition for decades, before yesterday's elections, the opposition uniting forces under the name of United Democratic Forces (UDCF) seriously hoped that Lukashenko, renewing his term as president for the fourth time in questionable elections, on the trail of the 2006 constitutional amendment, would "allow" the presence of a few opposition MPs in parliament this time.
