They're pointing fingers at the MP3 player, they're putting the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for extended periods of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announced, citing the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the EU's unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) published today in a communiqué in Brussels.
"The scientific report states that 5-10% of those who for at least 5 years listen to music at full volume using portable music devices for more than one hour a day and a week are at risk of permanent hearing loss.
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use mobile music devices and mobile phones at high volume may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably", says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data", continues the EU official, "this is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public domain.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies.'
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should take a decision on the application of the directive to the Member States.
'The scientists confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now consider with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical instruments and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data well by using solutions such as reducing noise levels and exposure duration.
The European Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week exceed the current limits on the maximum level of noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music for extended periods of time in such conditions may lose their hearing permanently after five years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 to 10 million people in the EU.
In Rome, Alemanno has ordered the Commission to set off for the future of the capital.
We start today, we finish in March, we draw the money in June.
This is the schedule set by the Capitol for the work of the Commission for the Future of Rome, which took place this morning at the new headquarters behind the Thermes de Caracalla.
In six months' time, President Antonio Marzano and the 49 other Commissioners will draw up the directives for Rome.
In March, when they are completed, the Committee and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects, so that the Strategic Plan for Rome with the official stamp of the Capitol and its mayor Gianni Alemanno will be presented in June.
"The Commission is absolutely independent; all political, social and cultural ideas are represented there", emphasises Alemanno.
No overlapping roles, just the desire to have a corner to develop a big project for Rome.
In March, she will have completed her tasks and then disappear, because this experiment must have a precise time duration.
In June the mayor will announce the strategic plan for the future of Rome Capital, which is the result of the work of the Commission".
For those who accuse the Commission of being useless, since its opinions will not be binding, Alemanno replies: 'It all depends on the work the Commission will be able to do and the quality of its proposals.
If quality is there, as in France thanks to the Attali Commission, as in Rome, I am sure, its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics is overwhelmed by the day-to-day management and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to look ahead and further into a deeper perspective, working seriously on the development of Rome and its future".
The mayor of Rome also wanted to emphasize that "this Commission is not a useless body or a bureaucratic body: it is absolutely free, and will not cost the citizens of Rome a euro, and will be used to study and involve the best intellectuals who express themselves in the capital.
Germanno said that "a strategic reference plan, neither firm nor immobile, is needed to enable our city to improve itself, which it absolutely needs, while thinking about its future now in a united spirit".
The mayor of Rome said that the future would "not be limited to the usual communal boundaries, but look further not only in terms of the future metropolitan city and its legal status as capital, but also in terms of the role that Rome can and must play as the capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
