The elite are in danger.
The phenomenon was already evident a few days ago, with the House voting against the $700 billion bailout approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms this, reporting that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, even more divided between its former East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, conservative, hostile to "the Washingtonists" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern states.
The very soul that has been despotically made to feel with the vote I spoke of at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake has foretold or already caused: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the phenomena that have been taking place for some time, so that in the new climate they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these is the revival, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, in relation to a sort of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with foreign countries, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State.
This immediately creates a political problem for the ruling party, which is how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also electors.
In short, the crisis appears to be global economically but politically, it is almost only national.
The European Union, as always, divided between different interests and national strategies, cannot decide on any common policy.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit allocation: when you go through a difficult period, only the states have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back on track.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements which no market or international organization can ever have in an analogous way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that recent economic developments in the economy tend to attach to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, as we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of networks, increasingly sophisticated technology, non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future would have to settle our accounts more and more with rather intangible things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but are absolutely bound to a limited space, to a territory.
So whoever is sovereign, he certainly has more cards than whoever is not, that is, the one who is unlucky to live in a place without crops, oil and water.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, provides for a break.
Which says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for someone who can handle the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And then there's something even deeper, in a sense even more disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of alienation that tends to involve the entire management class in a growing number of Western countries.
This further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites up to now at their height, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership is underground, fueling a powerful and branching movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifests itself in the improvised electoral 'rebels' or, in the recent changes in the collective mood of the latter, from the conservative rise in Bavarian Austria, to the fall of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of the American Congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone might say, are finding it increasingly difficult, which is not current, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is strengthening, increasing and potentially agitating in a disproportionate way.
In view of all this, it seems frankly exaggerated to mention a current "mass rebellion" on the agenda.
But they say, keeping your eyes wide open, it's not without reason.
The superstick to walk on the walls.
Overcome the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
That's the goal of several American research centers, and today a team of four institutes has nearly succeeded.
With a sticker measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to hold a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The U.S. journal Science published the findings of researchers at the University of Dayton, the University of Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have drawn inspiration from geckos' legs, which are covered in microscopic hairs that ensure the animal's perfect grip.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the reptile's legs, and at the same time, it can easily detach itself from the wall", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
MARCHING ON THE WALL? " this material could be used as a temporary adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also looking for a new adhesives.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, researchers in California presented a glue made of microfiber-like hairs that self-cleans from dust when moving on a surface to ensure a perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Be careful with grapefruit juice, orange juice and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer because they are thirsty and rich in vitamins, when combined with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing their efficacy, depending on the case, with even serious health consequences.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, reminds us of the risks of fruit juices, whether bottled or fresh, when combined with the ingestion of certain medicines; at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he raises a new alarm: one glass of grapefruit juice, orange and apples is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital medicines, canceling out their beneficial effects and putting patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, stamina and neurological medicines to toxic levels.
RISK MEDICAMENTS - The Italian Medicines Agency itself reported the news in a two-year newsletter warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the dangers of this mixture and to be careful what they drink if they are taking medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT PAMPLAMELY - According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit medications.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices is long.
Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are usually immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies, which will need to change the information notes on medicines if necessary.
It is always worth reading the illustrative papers of the medicines you are taking, and if something is not clear, do not be impressed, but speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist", the expert told Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics is for Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a well-known New York Times editor.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy solutions.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman wrote in an article in the New York Times that the second event would have been more decisive than the first in terms of consequences for the history of the United States.
A prediction that sparked much controversy, and was criticized by economists for years, but now has proven true.
"I am surprised and even a little shocked by how quickly the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from public attention", Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the European Central Bank's Executive Committee, Krugman is a "high-value economist" but also a "very aggressive" disclosor, particularly critical of the Bush administration's excess liberalism.
Open Office, this is the third edition of the anti-Microsoft package.
Today is the day of the launch of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach ever more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
Following nearly a year of work by volunteer developers, supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office package is being shown to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen and the revised and less austere interface, to more important ones, such as the compatibility of the Apple Mac OS X operating system, and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest ISO standard version.
Open Office has paid particular attention to interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some module-specific functions, such as the one that reduces the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for e-mailing them, or for importing PDF files into the graphics module, keeping the page's original look.
Also on this front, it is possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical Adobe graphic format with elements of a worksheet or text editor.
Multi-person collaboration is an element that has been improved within applications: in the worksheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts over changes, in the development of texts, as each collaborator is assigned a comment color for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some of the features of OpenOffice to the web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they should issue the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and is added to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is also available as usual for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to the home or workplace.
And if the theme of free can be a way to spread it to homes, it is precisely in business that Open Office is now facing the big challenge, already relying on various projects in public administration and schools.
The Commission has also proposed a number of measures to improve the quality of the services provided by SMEs.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the video equivalent of Word; Calc, the spreadsheet intended to replace Excel; Impress, for rival PowerPoint presentations; Dbase, as the famous Access, is the program that allows you to work on databases; and finally Drwa is the graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and given that we now have almost 3.600 million miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the expected figure.
