Students who are victims of expensive rent, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market is not in crisis
According to the latest survey by the Sunia, the rental union, renting a simple room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples, 600 euros in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached such serious dimensions that it excludes entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families from other countries have to bear", explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia study office.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free, unregistered, unlimited rental contracts, sub-leases.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of taxation are needed to calm prices.
In Milan, a bed in the Brianza area costs about 450 euros; a single room costs 650 euros minimum (Bande Nere area), an average of 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area).
In Florence, the average bed costs 350/400 euros, a bedroom about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the University, it costs 250/280 euros for a double bed, and 370-500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas near the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), the cost is about 600 euros for a single bed and 450 euros for a double bed.
Slightly lower values (€550 for a single) for the areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
The only way to save money is to move away from the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, 450 euros for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar areas.
In Naples, a bed costs 300 to 400 euros, a single one costs 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, you have to count 250/350 euros for a bed, at least 350 for a single one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, in cities such as Perugia, where rents are often taken by extracommunity students, there is another anomaly: rents demanded from foreign students are increased by 25/30% compared to those applied to Italians.
Goodbye old Paradiso cinema, the cities are lightening up the historic halls.
Historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without a cinema is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image presented by the director Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the emergence of large multi-screen theatres on the periphery and the death of single-screen theatres in central urban areas, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear is often to be found in historical and memorable places, "it's like a friend of mine disappearing, someone we know, with whom we shared a journey and so many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, a film that gave Tornatore its first Oscar and Grand Prix of the Cannes Jury 20 years ago, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia for a lost way of life in cinema, can be lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, tell the whole story: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the theatres in the main cities have paid the most: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 lost single cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the main cause of their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, as the three Italian regions have recorded the most new multiplex cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italy's economy has grown irrationally", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to ensure the survival of existing ones, because when a hall is closed in a city, not all of these frequenters are necessarily willing to go to multiplexes.
The Commission has not yet taken any further steps to ensure that the Commission's budgetary commitments are met.
It is a shame that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government is not respecting the existing laws.
The sector would need between EUR 16 and EUR 18 million a year to support it.
The first Italian city concerned about the closures, Bologna, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single cinemas in historic and outlying centres.
The regulations include tax relief measures for managers and public mobility benefits: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and special parking and parking rates will be applied.
"This is an initiative that I like", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by implementing further measures.
However, it is clear that to counter the super power of multiplexes, traditional theatres also need to improve sound and image quality, as today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place where I grew up and was a teenager, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much of shared emotion, I turn to the other side to avoid seeing the signs blackened by dust.
Political ties with ndrangheta, arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro.
 The Mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to standardize the choices of the City Hall to the interests of the Piromalli clan".
The Magistrates of the Directorate for the Prevention of Mafia in Calabria have filed heavy charges against the Mayor and Deputy Mayor of Gioia Tauro, Giorgio Dal Torrione, as well as Rosario Schiavione and the Mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, who were arrested this morning for outside competition for mafia association.
The handcuffs also go to Gioacchino Piromalli, the former mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his young son, the lawyer, who is the boss' namesake, already convicted of association with mafia-type criminals, and to pay 10 million euros.
"An affront to legal and moral norms, and above all to common sense", the prosecutors write, the two local administrations had expressed their willingness to pay for consultations with Mr Piromalli.
"The clan would have been granted official entry into the town halls", the judges wrote, "facilitating the already considerable possibilities for control and guidance of public administration".
