He shouted outrage when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He accused the then Deputy Minister of the Interior, Marco Minniti, of manipulating the whole thing for a political issue, but given the arrest request signed this morning, the judges explain that the Piromalli clan even managed to request the variation of the A3 project.
The interceptions ordered against Dal Torrione, the prime ministers write, have revealed "the willingness to marry the demands of a businessman, representing a better known group, close to the Piromalli, unifying the choices of the public administration to the interests of the clan.
When the energy comes from the waves, now the big ones are going to jump.
This is a massive deposit that occupies over 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have looked at, and now they're trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, at the same time as the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When oil prices fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalists and the new rise in oil are giving the sector a big boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by systems operating at sea.
This would be twice as much as nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides.
Colossus is on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it was a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more candidates from these companies, which have always been committed to traditional energy, are turning to marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies", a spokesman for the oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating opportunities for cooperation with us".
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a deliberate permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to produce a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that in Alaska, the United States is still extracting oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are tracing the energy path from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are unknown, observers say, indicate growing interest.
