After the waves, the tides.
A special interest, they say to the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, is due at this time to the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it's precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, among others, are looking to the coast, investing $7.5 million in 2008 and projecting up to $35 million in 2009.
